Q2: Is there a correlation between discount percentage and review ratings?

Analysis: Scatter plot of DISCOUNT_PCT vs. REVIEW_RATING with CATEGORY as hue.

Insight: Do heavily discounted items have lower ratings (potential liquidation of poor-quality products)?

In [11]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy import stats

# Calculate discount percentage
df['DISCOUNT_PCT'] = ((df['PRICE_RETAIL'] - df['PRICE_CURRENT']) / df['PRICE_RETAIL']) * 100

# Create the scatter plot with category as hue
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x='DISCOUNT_PCT',
    y='REVIEW_RATING',
    hue='CATEGORY',
    alpha=0.6,
    palette='viridis',
    s=100
)

# Add trendline for overall relationship
sns.regplot(
    data=df,
    x='DISCOUNT_PCT',
    y='REVIEW_RATING',
    scatter=False,
    color='black',
    line_kws={'linestyle': '--', 'alpha': 0.5}
)

# Customize the plot
plt.title('Discount Percentage vs. Review Rating by Category', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Discount Percentage (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Review Rating (out of 5)', fontsize=12)
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()

# Calculate correlation coefficients
pearson_corr, pearson_p = stats.pearsonr(df['DISCOUNT_PCT'], df['REVIEW_RATING'])
spearman_corr, spearman_p = stats.spearmanr(df['DISCOUNT_PCT'], df['REVIEW_RATING'])

print(f"Pearson Correlation: {pearson_corr:.3f} (p-value: {pearson_p:.3e})")
print(f"Spearman Correlation: {spearman_corr:.3f} (p-value: {spearman_p:.3e})")

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Bonus: Category-level correlations
category_corrs = df.groupby('CATEGORY').apply(
    lambda x: stats.spearmanr(x['DISCOUNT_PCT'], x['REVIEW_RATING'])[0]
).sort_values()

print("\nCategory-Specific Spearman Correlations:")
print(category_corrs)

Key Insight:¶

There's a very weak but statistically significant trend where higher discounts are slightly associated with higher ratings overall. This suggests discounts aren't primarily used to liquidate low-quality products.

New Arrivals & Clothing: Higher discounts correlate with better ratings. Possible reasons:

  • Strategic discounts on popular/high-quality new items to drive traffic.

  • Customers appreciate markdowns on desirable items.

Jewelry & Shoes: Near-zero/slightly negative correlations suggest discounts may be used for clearance of underperforming items.

Business Recommendations¶

For New Arrivals & Clothing:

  • Continue using discounts as a marketing tool for high-quality items.

  • Consider dynamic pricing: Higher initial prices followed by strategic discounts.

For Jewelry & Shoes:

  • Investigate why discounted items have slightly lower ratings:

  • Is discounting being used for defective/returned items?

Are customers disappointed by discounted luxury goods?

  • For categories with positive correlations: Bundle discounts with loyalty programs.

  • For negative-correlation categories: Use discounts more selectively (e.g., seasonal only).

3.Promotional Effectiveness¶

Q5: Do products under promotion (PROMOTION) have higher review counts (REVIEW_COUNT)?

In [20]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy import stats

# Clean promotion data (assuming 'PROMOTION' has NaN for non-promoted items)
df['PROMOTION_STATUS'] = np.where(df['PROMOTION'].notna(), 'Promoted', 'Not Promoted')

# 1. Descriptive Statistics
promo_stats = df.groupby('PROMOTION_STATUS')['REVIEW_COUNT'].describe()
print("Review Count Statistics:\n", promo_stats)

# 2. Visual Comparison
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Boxplot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='PROMOTION_STATUS', y='REVIEW_COUNT', showfliers=False)
plt.title('Review Count Distribution')
plt.ylabel('Review Count')
plt.xlabel('')

# Violin plot (shows density)
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sns.violinplot(data=df, x='PROMOTION_STATUS', y='REVIEW_COUNT', inner='quartile', cut=0)
plt.title('Density Distribution')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 3. Mann-Whitney U Test (non-parametric alternative to t-test)
promoted = df[df['PROMOTION_STATUS'] == 'Promoted']['REVIEW_COUNT']
not_promoted = df[df['PROMOTION_STATUS'] == 'Not Promoted']['REVIEW_COUNT']

stat, p = stats.mannwhitneyu(promoted, not_promoted, alternative='two-sided')
print(f"\nMann-Whitney U Test Results: U={stat:,.0f}, p={p:.4f}")

# 4. Effect Size (Common Language Effect Size)
def cles(x, y):
    """Probability that random x > random y"""
    return np.mean([np.random.choice(x) > np.random.choice(y) for _ in range(1000)])

effect_size = cles(promoted, not_promoted)
print(f"Effect Size: {effect_size:.2f} (probability promoted > non-promoted)")

# 5. Category-Level Analysis (Bonus)
if 'CATEGORY' in df.columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.barplot(data=df, x='CATEGORY', y='REVIEW_COUNT', hue='PROMOTION_STATUS', 
                estimator=np.median, errorbar=None)
    plt.title('Median Review Count by Category and Promotion Status')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

import dash
from dash import dcc, html, Input, Output
import plotly.express as px
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats

# Load and prepare data
df = pd.read_csv('nordstrom_product_data.csv')
df['PROMOTION_STATUS'] = np.where(df['PROMOTION'].notna(), 'Promoted', 'Not Promoted')
df['DISCOUNT_PCT'] = ((df['PRICE_RETAIL'] - df['PRICE_CURRENT']) / df['PRICE_RETAIL']) * 100

# Initialize Dash app
app = dash.Dash(__name__)

app.layout = html.Div([
    html.H1("Nordstrom Product Performance Dashboard", style={'textAlign': 'center'}),
    
    # Filters Row
    html.Div([
        html.Div([
            html.Label("Select Department:"),
            dcc.Dropdown(
                id='dept-filter',
                options=[{'label': dept, 'value': dept} for dept in df['DEPARTMENT'].unique()],
                value='Clothing',
                clearable=False
            )
        ], style={'width': '30%', 'display': 'inline-block'}),
        
        html.Div([
            html.Label("Discount Range:"),
            dcc.RangeSlider(
                id='discount-slider',
                min=0,
                max=100,
                step=5,
                marks={i: f'{i}%' for i in range(0, 101, 20)},
                value=[0, 100]
            )
        ], style={'width': '65%', 'display': 'inline-block', 'float': 'right'})
    ], style={'padding': '20px 0px'}),
    
    # Main Visualizations
    html.Div([
        html.Div([
            dcc.Graph(id='promo-impact-plot')
        ], style={'width': '48%', 'display': 'inline-block'}),
        
        html.Div([
            dcc.Graph(id='discount-rating-plot')
        ], style={'width': '48%', 'display': 'inline-block', 'float': 'right'})
    ]),
    
    # Secondary Visualizations
    html.Div([
        dcc.Graph(id='category-breakdown')
    ], style={'padding': '20px 0px'}),
    
    # Key Metrics Cards
    html.Div([
        html.Div(id='mann-whitney-card', style={
            'width': '32%',
            'display': 'inline-block',
            'backgroundColor': '#f8f9fa',
            'padding': '10px',
            'borderRadius': '5px',
            'marginRight': '1%'
        }),
        
        html.Div(id='effect-size-card', style={
            'width': '32%',
            'display': 'inline-block',
            'backgroundColor': '#f8f9fa',
            'padding': '10px',
            'borderRadius': '5px',
            'marginRight': '1%'
        }),
        
        html.Div(id='top-category-card', style={
            'width': '32%',
            'display': 'inline-block',
            'backgroundColor': '#f8f9fa',
            'padding': '10px',
            'borderRadius': '5px'
        })
    ])
])

# Callback for promo impact plot
@app.callback(
    Output('promo-impact-plot', 'figure'),
    [Input('dept-filter', 'value'),
     Input('discount-slider', 'value')]
)
def update_promo_plot(department, discount_range):
    filtered_df = df[(df['DEPARTMENT'] == department) & 
                    (df['DISCOUNT_PCT'] >= discount_range[0]) & 
                    (df['DISCOUNT_PCT'] <= discount_range[1])]
    
    fig = px.box(filtered_df, 
                 x='PROMOTION_STATUS', 
                 y='REVIEW_COUNT',
                 color='PROMOTION_STATUS',
                 title=f"Review Count Engagement in {department}",
                 log_y=True)
    
    fig.update_layout(showlegend=False)
    return fig

# Callback for discount-rating plot
@app.callback(
    Output('discount-rating-plot', 'figure'),
    [Input('dept-filter', 'value'),
     Input('discount-slider', 'value')]
)
def update_discount_plot(department, discount_range):
    filtered_df = df[(df['DEPARTMENT'] == department) & 
                    (df['DISCOUNT_PCT'] >= discount_range[0]) & 
                    (df['DISCOUNT_PCT'] <= discount_range[1])]
    
    fig = px.scatter(filtered_df,
                     x='DISCOUNT_PCT',
                     y='REVIEW_RATING',
                     color='CATEGORY',
                     title=f"Discount vs. Ratings in {department}",
                     trendline="lowess")
    
    fig.update_traces(marker=dict(size=8, opacity=0.6))
    return fig

# Callback for category breakdown
@app.callback(
    Output('category-breakdown', 'figure'),
    [Input('dept-filter', 'value')]
)
def update_category_plot(department):
    temp_df = df[df['DEPARTMENT'] == department]
    category_comparison = temp_df.groupby(['CATEGORY', 'PROMOTION_STATUS'])['REVIEW_COUNT'] \
                          .median().unstack()
    category_comparison['PCT_DIFF'] = ((category_comparison['Promoted'] - \
                                      category_comparison['Not Promoted']) / \
                                      category_comparison['Not Promoted']) * 100
    
    fig = px.bar(category_comparison.reset_index(),
                 x='CATEGORY',
                 y='PCT_DIFF',
                 title=f"Promotion Impact by Category in {department}",
                 color='PCT_DIFF',
                 color_continuous_scale='RdYlGn')
    
    fig.update_layout(coloraxis_showscale=False)
    return fig

# Callback for metrics cards
@app.callback(
    [Output('mann-whitney-card', 'children'),
     Output('effect-size-card', 'children'),
     Output('top-category-card', 'children')],
    [Input('dept-filter', 'value')]
)
def update_metrics(department):
    temp_df = df[df['DEPARTMENT'] == department]
    promoted = temp_df[temp_df['PROMOTION_STATUS'] == 'Promoted']['REVIEW_COUNT']
    not_promoted = temp_df[temp_df['PROMOTION_STATUS'] == 'Not Promoted']['REVIEW_COUNT']
    
    # Mann-Whitney test
    stat, p = stats.mannwhitneyu(promoted, not_promoted)
    mw_card = [
        html.H4("Statistical Significance"),
        html.P(f"U = {stat:,.0f}"),
        html.P(f"p-value = {p:.4f}", style={'color': 'green' if p < 0.05 else 'red'})
    ]
    
    # Effect size
    def cles(x, y):
        return np.mean([np.random.choice(x) > np.random.choice(y) for _ in range(1000)])
    
    es = cles(promoted, not_promoted)
    es_card = [
        html.H4("Effect Size"),
        html.P(f"CLES = {es:.2f}"),
        html.P("(Probability promoted > non-promoted)")
    ]
    
    # Top performing category
    category_comparison = temp_df.groupby(['CATEGORY', 'PROMOTION_STATUS'])['REVIEW_COUNT'] \
                          .median().unstack()
    best_category = category_comparison['PCT_DIFF'].idxmax()
    best_value = category_comparison['PCT_DIFF'].max()
    
    top_card = [
        html.H4("Best Performing Category"),
        html.P(best_category),
        html.P(f"+{best_value:.0f}% engagement", style={'color': 'green'})
    ]
    
    return mw_card, es_card, top_card

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True, port=8050)
